Obtaining the data

load("twoMillion311calls.RData")
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
df <- select(df, CreatedDate, ClosedDate,Agency, AgencyName,ComplaintType,Descriptor,Borough,IncidentZip)
df <- df |> distinct()
df$responsetime <- as.integer(mdy_hms(df$ClosedDate) - mdy_hms(df$CreatedDate))
Warning: NAs introduced by coercion to integer range
df <- df |> drop_na()
df <- df[df$responsetime>0,]
dim(df)
[1] 1419955       9

My main data frame consists of about 1.4 million rows and 9 relevant columns. I will analyze this data set.

Part 2: Visual Description

#PLot 1
options(scipen = 999)

df7 <- dfa |>
  group_by(Agency,Borough) |>
  subset(select=c(Agency,Borough)) |>
  summarize(Complaints = n()) |>
  filter(Complaints > 10000)

df8 <- df7 |>
  group_by(Agency) |>
  summarize(totComplaints=sum(Complaints))
df9 <- full_join(df7,df8)
df9 |>
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Agency,totComplaints),y=Complaints,fill=Borough)) +
  xlab("Category") +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("Number of complaints by Agency and Borough")

This stacked bar plot shows the number of complaints by Agency and Borough in the data set. This plot shows that there is a fairly even spread of Number of complaints by Borough for each Agency. In addition, most complaints from Boroughs âBRONXâ and âBROOKLYNâ seem to be handled by the HPD.

#Plot 2
df1 <- df |>
  group_by(ComplaintType,Borough) |>
  subset(select=c(ComplaintType,Borough)) |>
  summarize(Complaints = n()) |>
  filter(Complaints > 10000)

df2 <- df1 |>

This bar plot shows that Heating was by far the most frequent type of complaint in the data set followed by General Construction and Street Condition.

This violin plot shows that for a Complaint type of Blocked Driveway, there is a large density of entries with a relatively low response time. Also, Street Condition seems to have no trend in response time, and response time for the other complaint types are very similar.

Part 3: Regression

dfR <- select(df,Agency,ComplaintType,Descriptor,Borough,IncidentZip,responsetime)

dfR <- dfR |> drop_na()

dfR$Agency <- as.factor(dfR$Agency)
dfR$ComplaintType <- as.factor(dfR$ComplaintType)
dfR$Descriptor <- as.factor(dfR$Descriptor)
dfR$Borough <- as.factor(dfR$Borough)
dfR$IncidentZip <- as.factor(dfR$IncidentZip)

I make a new data frame for Regression and convert relevant columns to Factor.

After running many trial and error linear models using different variable combinations, the best regression model I came up with includes the variables Agency, ComplaintType and Borough. These are the variables that affect the response time the most. My R squared value of 14%, for such a large data set, supports my claim.

Part 4: Regression Diagnostics

model<-(lm(responsetime~Agency+ComplaintType+Borough,data=dfR))

Residuals Versus Fitted: Firstly, other than the point 1295366, there are no notable outliers - I think this point can be omitted from further analysis since it is the only outlier out of such a large data set of over a million values. Secondly, the solid red line seems to be aligned with the dashed zero line, indicating that the residuals have a mean of approximately zero. Third, there is no pattern in the residuals or no curve, widening or narrowing shape of the graph to further consider in the analysis.

Normal Q-Q: In this instance, the residuals do not comply with the dashed line at all, instead trailing at the start and spiking upwards in value as the line continues. Therefore, we can assume that the residuals are not normally distributed.

Scale Location: Here, the red line is an upwards slope, meaning that there is large variability in the standardized residuals - violation of the assumption of constant variance, also known as homoscedasticity.

Residuals Versus Leverage: For this chart, the points 1136471 and 977611 should likely be removed as they lie outside cookâs distance, even though they have good leverage values. Other than that, most of the points seem to have very low leverage values.

Final Conclusion: In Summary, after a thorough analysis of the New York 311 calls data set, I believe the variables that affect the response time of a complaint are the Borough, the type of complaint and the agency handling the complaint. Other variables like IncidentZip seem to have little to no affect on the values of response time.
